# Task assignments via company-inbox

When you receive an event whose `source` is `"company-inbox"`, it is a task
assignment from the-company task graph. The event `meta` carries:

- `task_id` ‚Äî the UUID you PATCH against `PATCH /api/tasks/{task_id}`.
- `root_id` ‚Äî the root task this descends from. Equals `task_id` for a root.
- `title`, `description` ‚Äî what you have been asked to do.
- `payload` ‚Äî task-specific input. May be empty.
- `parent_id`, `company_id`, `created_by`, `deadline_at` ‚Äî context for the
  task tree; not always present.

The `task_id` is the field you need for every PATCH. Do not look for it in
the event body ‚Äî read it from `meta.task_id`.

Your job runs in three steps: Decide, Work, Close.

1. Decide. PATCH the task from `pending` to `accepted` if you will do it.
   If it is misrouted, outside your competence, or obviously broken, PATCH
   it to `rejected` with the reason in `result.error.message`. Do not
   ignore the event ‚Äî leaving a task in `pending` lets the janitor expire
   it later, which is indistinguishable from "the system is broken".

2. Work. PATCH `accepted` to `in_progress` when you actually start. Do
   the work. If you need to delegate sub-tasks, `POST
   /api/tasks/{task_id}/spawn` ‚Äî see the goal-integration spec for the
   payload shape.

3. Close. PATCH `in_progress` to `done` with `result.payload` set, or to
   `failed` with `result.error` set. The shape is below.

The state machine does not allow shortcuts. The legal transitions are:

    pending      ‚Üí accepted | rejected
    accepted     ‚Üí in_progress | rejected
    in_progress  ‚Üí done | failed | blocked | rejected
    blocked      ‚Üí in_progress | rejected

Going straight from `pending` to `done` returns 422 `illegal_transition`.
Walk the states. `blocked` is for the kind of stuck that needs a human or
sibling-agent decision; raise an approval and stop, do not loop.

Result payload shape ‚Äî success:

    {
      "payload": <task-specific artifact>,
      "notes": "<free-text observation, optional>",
      "warnings": ["<non-fatal issues to flag>"]
    }

Result payload shape ‚Äî failure (use with `failed` or `rejected`):

    {
      "error": {
        "code": "<short stable identifier>",
        "message": "<one-line human-readable>",
        "details": <optional structured>
      },
      "notes": "<context about what was tried>"
    }

`payload` / `error` / `notes` are the agreed slots. Add task-specific
top-level keys if you genuinely need them, but those three are the
contract every consumer reads first.

Failure mode to avoid: PATCHing to `done` with empty `result.payload`
and no `error` block. That is "silencing the task" ‚Äî looks successful,
delivered nothing. If you genuinely have no artifact, PATCH `failed` with
`error.code = "no_artifact"` and explain in `error.message`.

Idempotent re-injection. If you receive a task assignment for a `task_id`
that is already in a terminal status (`done`, `failed`, `rejected`,
`expired`), do nothing and log the fact. The channel's dedup usually
prevents this, but a boot-time replay can slip one through. Re-PATCHing a
terminal task returns 422; staying silent is the correct response.
